# Why Do We Separate Everything?

Suppose we keep everything in one folder.

```text
BloodReportAnalyzer/

app.py

logo.png

database.sql

design.pdf

API.txt

random.txt

notes.docx
```

After six months...

Nobody knows where anything is.

Instead:

```text
mobile/

backend/

docs/

database/

assets/
```

Everything is organized.

---

# GitHub

Every professional software project uses **Git** and **GitHub**.

Git helps us:

* Save versions of our code
* Go back if something breaks
* Work safely
* Track changes

GitHub helps us:

* Store the project online
* Collaborate with others
* Back up the code

Think of GitHub as **Google Drive for software projects**, but with version history.

---

# Project Documentation

Every project needs documentation.

Inside:

```text
docs/
```

We'll keep:

* Product requirements
* MVP roadmap
* Database design
* AI prompts
* API documentation
* User feedback
* Future ideas

This becomes the project's knowledge base.

---

# README.md

Every GitHub project starts with a README.

Example:

```text
Blood Report Analyzer

AI-powered health report analyzer.

Features:

• Upload reports

• OCR

• AI explanations

• Report history

• Trend analysis
```

A good README helps anyone understand the project quickly.

---

# Issue Tracking

As the project grows, you'll discover:

* Bugs
* New ideas
* Improvements

Instead of remembering everything, write them down.

Example:

```text
Issue #1

OCR misses Vitamin D values.

-----------------

Issue #2

Improve login screen.

-----------------

Issue #3

Add PDF export.
```

This prevents ideas from getting lost.

